headline: Saks Global obtains court approval for $400 million in rescue financing
summary:
STORY: A U.S. bankruptcy judge on Wednesday (January 14) granted initial approval of Saks Global’s bankruptcy financing.

It will allow the company to draw on $400 million in new cash despite an objection from Saks' estranged business partner Amazon.com.

Saks' chief restructuring officer Mark Weinstein said during the hearing the company would be "dead in the water" without the new money.

And plans to use it to pay vendors and the company's 17,000 employees.

The luxury retail company filed for bankruptcy on Tuesday with $3.4 billion of debt.

That's after its merger with Neiman Marcus caused cash shortfalls that prevented Saks from reliably replenishing inventory at its stores.

Saks Global's attorney said stores remain open for business and that the firm has no concern about weakening customer demand.

Before approving the bankruptcy loan, the judge overruled an objection by online retail giant Amazon.

It had argued its $475 million equity investment in Saks would become "worthless" if the bankruptcy proceeds with the current financing arrangement.

Amazon's attorney said at the hearing that it has "little to no confidence" Saks can successfully emerge from bankruptcy.

Long loved by the rich and famous, Saks never fully recovered from the COVID pandemic, as competition from online outlets rose.

The first data center is being built in Brandenburg, Germany, and more will be built in other parts of Europe.

headline: Amazon Loses First Attempt to Block Saks Bankruptcy Funding
summary: The online giant claimed the luxury retailer breached a deal to sell Saks products on its website and that its equity investment in the now bankrupt business is “presumptively worthless.”  After a late-night, 7.5-hour-long court battle, Saks won access to about $400 million in cash, but must return in the coming weeks to seek final approval of the entire, $1.75 billion financing package.  Amazon and other creditors that also oppose the financing, can try again to convince US Bankruptcy Judge Alfredo Perez to scrap, or alter, the debt deal.

headline: Rio Tinto to supply copper to Amazon for AI data centers
summary: Rio Tinto said on Thursday it would supply copper that it leaches from an Arizona mine to Amazon.com ​for use in the tech giant's artificial intelligence data centers.  The ‌move underscores the rampant push by the AI industry for access to supplies of copper ‌and other critical minerals that are used to build wiring, cables, circuit boards and other electronic parts.  AI sector growth is expected to boost global copper demand 50% by 2040, although analysts have warned supplies could fall far ⁠short, sparking a rush to ‌ensure access.

headline: Talen Energy Stock Jumps on $3.5 Billion Deal to ‘Enhance’ Data-Center Offerings

The energy-infrastructure company said Thursday it had signed a definitive agreement with investment firm Energy Capital Partners to acquire three power plants, two in Ohio and one in Indiana.  The deal consists of roughly approximately $2.6 billion in cash and $900 million in Talen stock.
